  <h2>The question</h2>
  <p>Hindi is morphologically rich — words carry a lot of grammatical information through inflection, and that creates sparsity problems that English-focused architectures weren't really designed for. I wanted to know which architecture handles next-word prediction best when the training data is small and the language is hard.</p>

  <h2>What I ran</h2>
  <p>Five architectures trained on 10,000 sentences from CC-100 Hindi: a count-based bigram baseline with Laplace smoothing, a single-layer Vanilla RNN, a single-layer LSTM with weight tying, the same LSTM with 0.3 dropout, and a two-layer stacked LSTM. I also included a BiLSTM as a non-causal reference ceiling — it sees future tokens, so its numbers aren't directly comparable, but it shows where the performance ceiling sits if you remove the causal constraint. Evaluation was on 2,000 held-out sentences, with UNK tokens excluded from accuracy calculations. Most models were averaged over three seeds, though the Vanilla RNN and the plain LSTM baseline were each only run once.</p>

  <h2>What I found</h2>
  <p>The Vanilla RNN won — 18.7% top-1 accuracy, 218 perplexity, 285K parameters, beating every LSTM variant on every metric (though it's a single run, not averaged like most of the others). Among the LSTM variants themselves, more architecture didn't clearly help: the plain single-layer LSTM was actually the weakest of the three at 15.4%, while adding dropout (16.4%) or stacking a second layer (16.3%) each recovered a bit of ground without coming close to the Vanilla RNN. With only 10,000 training sentences, none of the LSTM's extra capacity translated into an advantage. The bigram baseline sat at 1245 perplexity, which puts the scale of the gap in perspective. The non-causal BiLSTM hit 83.9% top-1 accuracy, which shows how much future context matters for Hindi sentence structure — but that's the context window you don't get at inference time, so it's the ceiling you're always chasing.</p>
